snippet.title: How to make FACE MASK | DIY Sew Mask | Kako napraviti Masku za Lice
snippet.description:
Learn how to make Face Mask in a very easy way. You can sew it with a hand or machine. 
Naucite kako brzo i lako napraviti zastitinu masku za lice

Currently, the supply of surgical masks is at a critical
all-time low throughout the entire nation. As a
community of sewists, this is a great way we can band
together and make a huge difference in this time of
need!
While handmade fabric face masks are NOT a
substitution for N95 masks, in times of emergency, the
CDC may allow handmade fabric masks to be used
when critical shortages take place. You can read more
from the CDC here on the use of homemade masks
here:https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019

According to the CDC website "homemade masks
should ideally be used in combination with a face
shield that covers the entire front (that extends to the
chin or below) and sides of the face."
In addition to helping medical staff during critical
shortages, these masks can be used at home as well.
While wearing homemade face masks will not prevent against catching a respiratory illness, they can help
reduce the spread of large particles when someone
sneezes or coughs.

snippet.title: How to Make the Best Face Mask, No Sewing (Don't use Cotton or Vac Bags!)
snippet.description:
I spent almost a month to get this right - This face mask is the closest you can get to an N95 equivalent face mask with common materials.  No sewing, no cotton ("cloth / fabric"). This mask is a far better homemade option compared to cloth facemasks for both filtration and most importantly fitment. This can be batch made in 10 minutes and is washable / reusable. This face mask uses non-woven polypropylene and is far better than a cotton (cloth) mask or even surgical mask (which leak on the sides). Your results obviously could vary depending on materials available. It isn't a replacement to a N95 or P2 Respirator. A fit tested N95 or P2 respirator is always best however this should be preserved for health care workers.

As a disclaimer though-  This video should be interpreted as theory, my own experimentation & entertainment only. Seek professional advise, do your own research and use these instructions at your own risk.

snippet.title: „ÄêDIY Face Mask ‚Äì 8 Steps in Making Protective Gear„Äë
snippet.description:
No surgical mask?. What shall I do? Let‚Äôs make DIY protective gear as an alternative in case of shortage of face mask.

Making DIY makeshift protective gear
Conditions of making DIY protective gear
‚Ä¢ Materials are relatively safe and reliable
‚Ä¢ With certain extent of protection function
‚Ä¢ Low-cost production
‚Ä¢ Readily available household items
‚Ä¢ Materials are easy to buy. No need for snapping up.

Materials and Tools:
1. Kitchen paper
2. Thick and breathable facial tissue paper
3. Rubber bands
4. Hole puncher
5. Adhesive tape ‚Äì 2 inch wide 
6. Binder clips
7. Scissors
8. Plastic-coated wires
9. A pair of glasses
10. Transparent plastic file folder

8 steps to make DIY protective gear:  
1. Wash your hands thoroughly and clean your materials (with hand rub or soap) 
2. Put one piece of kitchen paper on top of another at 90 degrees (to form the filter layer of a mask)
Note: Avoid overlapping the pattern on the kitchen paper as this would reduce its filtering function. 
Or use 2 different brands of kitchen paper (to form the filter layer of a mask)
3. Place a piece of thick tissue paper on top of the kitchen paper as the inner layer of the mask, (to form the water-absorbing layer of the face mask)
4. Use an adhesive tape to seal off the two sides of the mask (1 inch on each side)
5. Punch two holes on each sealed side 
6. Attach the plastic-coated wire with paper tape to the top edge of the mask to make the nose bridge wire. Glasses can be used to fix the position of nose bridge if no such wires available. 
Note: Do not use metallic wires without plastic-coating to avoid hurting eyes or face.
7. Tie 4 rubber bands/strings through the holes on the mask‚Äôs sides and adjust the length. (Ensure the face mask fit properly over the face. Not too tight nor too loose.)
8. Cut the transparent plastic file folder into half. Attach one piece on the edge of the glasses with binder clips to prevent droplets from coming in. (to serve as the waterproof shield of the face mask)

 Friendly Reminder:             
‚Ä¢ The DIY face mask is only for temporary use in case of shortage of face mask.
‚Ä¢ Never reuse the DIY face mask.
‚Ä¢ Standard surgical mask is always preferable.

snippet.description:
https://www.makemasks2020.org/volunteer


Pattern (scroll down for more polished pdf copy): https://www.instructables.com/id/AB-Mask-for-a-Nurse-by-a-Nurse/?fbclid=IwAR21M51TOOpuAGWyDtMiav8h5tnwdS7U8iAF8_k3Y_d0WlwsnApD0pzoG4s

MENTIONED ALTERATIONS: Marked 1/4‚Äù pleats 1‚Äù apart, stopping 5/8‚Äù away from bottom edge. Removed 1/4‚Äù seam allowance at the top and side edges. Used binding that is 1/2‚Äù wide when finished. 

All bias tape tutorials overcomplicate it like crazy - here is a breakdown if you‚Äôre unfamiliar with this process: 

Mark a line on the diagonal grain line of your fabric (AKA - the bias), from selvedge to selvedge. 
Use a ruler to mark lines 2‚Äù away from your first marking, also on the diagonal grain line of the fabric. 
Sew strips together and trim seam allowance between strips to 1/4‚Äù - press
Fold the raw edges inward by 1/2‚Äù to the center of the strip. Press. 

DONE!

‚ú©Links‚ú©

Hospitals requesting masks: https://docs.google.com/document/d/12a5YO0Z9RpHZk9Zkzl4NOj9CbjzhFfoKjPLFFC-21LU/edit

CDC on masks: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/ppe-strategy/face-masks.html

Study on homemade masks reducing respiratory infections: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440799/

FDA on surgical masks: https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/personal-protective-equipment-infection-control/n95-respirators-and-surgical-masks-face-masks

Material effectiveness: https://smartairfilters.com/en/blog/best-materials-make-diy-face-mask-virus/
Really quick breakdown of masks vs viruses: https://smartairfilters.com/en/blog/diy-homemade-mask-protect-virus-coronavirus/

These are by no means all the articles I looked through, just some of the easier ones to find!


NOTE : This video is monetized to help cover material costs to construct these - I‚Äôve ordered 1000 yards of twill tape, 200 yards of binding, and used 20+ yards of fabric from my own stash. Any Adsense earnings beyond necessary to cover my supplies will be donated to other makers to help cover materials and shipping costs associated with these.
